text.__SUMMARY__:
Corymbia papillosa, commonly known as the Maningrida bloodwood, is a member of the genus Corymbia native to northern Australia.
The tree typically grows to a height of 8 metres (26 ft) and has thick, flaky and tessellated bark.It grows in flat areas in sandy soils with lateritic gravels and has a range limited to tropical areas in the Kimberley region of Western Australia, and the top end of the Northern Territory.
